08840nam a22009375i 9780774853873DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748538737 a10.59962/97807748538732doi  a(DE-B1597)662300  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQE720.B75.H35 2005eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a971.100aHaida Gwaii :bHuman History and Environment from the Time of Loon to the Time of the Iron People /ced. by Daryl W. Fedje, Rolf Mathewes. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b86 b&w illustrations, 35 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPacific Rim Archaeology00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tForeword -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tA Note on Radiocarbon Dating -- tPaleoenvironmental History -- tLate Quaternary Geology of Haida Gwaii and Surrounding Marine Areas -- tHecate Strait Paleoshorelines -- tTerrestrial Paleoecology of Haida Gwaii and the Continental Shelf: Vegetation, Climate, and Plant Resources of the Coastal Migration Route -- tVegetation History of Anthony Island, Haida Gwaii, and Its Relationship to Climate Change and Human Settlement -- tThe Evolution of Endemic Species in Haida Gwaii -- tHistory of the Vertebrate Fauna in Haida Gwaii -- tHaida Traditional History -- tTllsda Xaaydas Ḵ’aaygang.nga: Long, Long Ago Haida Ancient Stories -- tTaadl, Nang Kilslaas, and Haida -- tHaida History through Archaeological Research -- tOverview of Cultural History -- tMillennial Tides and Shifting Shores: Archaeology on a Dynamic Landscape -- tKilgii Gwaay: An Early Maritime Site in the South of Haida Gwaii -- tTest Excavations at Raised Beach Sites in Southern Haida Gwaii and Their Significance to Northwest Coast Archaeology -- tRaised Beach Archaeology in Northern Haida Gwaii: Preliminary Results from the Cohoe Creek Site -- tThe Graham Tradition -- tGwaii Haanas Settlement Archaeology -- tShoreline Settlement Patterns in Gwaii Haanas during the Early and Late Holocene -- tConclusion: Synthesis of Environmental and Archaeological Data -- tReferences -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe most isolated archipelago on the west coast of the Americas, inhabited for at least 10,500 years, Haida Gwaii has fascinated scientists, social scientists, historians, and inquisitive travellers for decades. This book brings together the results of extensive and varied field research by both federal agencies and independent researchers, and carefully integrates them with earlier archaeological, ethnohistorical, and paleoenvironmental work in the region. It imparts significant new information about the natural history of Haida Gwaii, also known as the Queen Charlotte Islands, and the adjacent areas of Hecate Strait. Chapters analyze new data on ice retreat, shoreline and sea level change, faunal communities, and culture history, providing a more comprehensive picture of the history of the islands from the late glacial through the prehistoric period, to the time of European contact, known to the Haida as the "time of the Iron People." Much of the archaeological work was conducted with the direct participation of members of the Haida Nation. As a complement to the scientific approach of the research, two chapters provide a Haida perspective, explaining the value of traditional oral records and recounting several oral histories, including that of Taadl, the loon, which takes us back to the beginning of time. This volume is a veritable compendium of knowledge, out of which emerges the human and environmental history of Haida Gwaii and its dynamic landscape. Haida Gwaii will be of interest to scholars and students in archaeology and anthropology, and those with an interest in the environmental and cultural history of Haida Gwaii.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHaida IndiansxHistory. 0aPaleoecologyzBritish ColumbiazHaida Gwaii. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 a(Barbara J. Wilson), Ḵii7iljuus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a(James Young), Nang Kiing.aay7uuans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAcheson, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcher, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrie, J. Vaughn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByun, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClague, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Kim W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedje, Daryl W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedje, Daryl W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFladmark, Knut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuujaaw,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHebda, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJosenham, Heiner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJosenhans, Heiner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJosenhans, Reiner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacourse, Terri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLake, Cynthia, 